> Start using the Oak-based index with more writer threads, to let it really shine (the microbenchmarks show that it becomes more attractive as the number of writers scales). This might require more far-fetched changes, which we might not fully appreciate at the moment, so let's discuss.

@ebortnik thanks! Your comment makes things more clear. I have a follow-up question on the above comment though. 

As I mentioned earlier, our previous work has focused on distributed data ingestion in which multiple tasks can run at the same time to ingest data into the same dataSource. Each task uses a few threads for indexing (basically read thread, persist thread and merge thread), but they can run in parallel in multiple middleManagers (or even same middleManager) so that faster ingestion could be achieved. It seems that your comment assumes that multi-thread indexing will bring us other benefits which is missing in distributed data ingestion. What kind of benefits can we expect with multi-thread indexing? And how is it different from what we can get from distributed indexing?

@jihoonson thanks! No, I havent really encountered data loss. Im asking because one of our scenario needs a short taskDuration and Im thinking about the feasibility.

Just curious, how does the kafka task know that the version should be v1 instead of v2? Doesnt the segment take the version directly from the lock?

Thanks
